bathing.html.title: Bathing
bathing.html.body:
Bathing
Video

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RjYHJsTzd4Y&feature=share

Supplies

Bouncy seat with big fluffy towel
basket container hairbrush, soap, washcloths

instructions

Firm hand on bottom and on head
warm cloth on top of chest
keep water running for sound
Soft baby cloth with no soap, wash face
baby wash, put right on wash cloth covering chest
wash arms and legs with that soap
clean bottoms on changing tables prior to bath
place soap on scalp, use baby brush to scrub in circular motion
cradle cap - skin mixes with oils and causes crusty crown


Rinse scalp
Rinse one last time everywhere
One hand under head, one hand gripping leg
Put into towel bouncy chair immediately
dry quickly

diapers.html.title: Diapers
diapers.html.body:
Diapers

Prepare, pop it open, and release inner plastic
Place underneath baby bottom, while baby is still wearing other diaper
stretch out plastic

have everything near you - blanket, pad, wipes, diapers, maybe diaper cream

Put child on flat surface - put head higher than body with wedge if possible
Always have 1 hand on baby all times
put clean diaper underneath dirty one
Open the dirty diaper, very slowly, cover it back up if they go while opening
Wipe the baby clean, lift legs of baby, wipe baby, if girl, front to back
Remove the dirty diaper and the wipes, leave wipes in diaper, use tabs to close dirty diaper
Apply diaper cream
Secure clean diaper - if umbilical cord stump, fold diaper down a bit

Before you remove diaper, rub wet baby wipe below belly button. This will make him urinate in the dirty diaper

Wipe diaper in vaseline if baby is circumcised
Rubbing alcohol and cue tip for belly button
Change diaper size when

first-weeks.html.title: First weeks
first-weeks.html.body:
Baby's first few weeks at home
Bonding

Hold your baby as much as you can
massage baby
Talk, sing, and read aloud

Soothing your baby

Hungry - feed baby even if just ate
Gassy - make sure baby isn't swallowing too much air. Burb after feeding
Hold your baby against your shoulder, upright in your lap, or face down accross your lap and gently pat or rub back


Diaper - change diaper, even if it's a little wet
Cold - skin to skin or swaddle
Too warm - take off clothes, after 10 minutes, temperature
Tired - swaddle & rock
Lonely - Cuddle near heart
Tense - Rock or walk, ride in stroller, soothing sounds, sing

First home

First few nights are crazy,
Swaddle, in nice large blanket

Swaddle

https://youtu.be/RhsYw61ZsO8
Don't want hips tight
Arms under bottom
Swaddle until about 3 months old

Soothing
Soothing at sleep times

Baby ferris wheel
Shush and rub your belly - shush louder than the baby
Shush and jiggle at midsection
Use pacifier - take pacifier as soon as eyes start to slowly close

Five S's
4 concepts
Missing 4th trimester

babies born too early

Calming reflex

few months after birth

5 S's

Swaddling - down - up down up approach
Side/Stomach position
Reverse breast feeding hold
Football hold
Over the shoulder hold


Shhhh sound - shhh loudly - Raise volume to match volume with baby, when they stop crying, white noise app or found
Swinging -
Start fast and jiggle
head jiggle more than body
Follow your baby's lead - swing at same ferocity baby cries


Sucking -
Try different nipples
don't force it
Use reverse psychology to keep from falling out
Repeat 10 to 20 times


Don't use pacifier for 2 to 3 weeks if breast feeding



Wean

Swinging - 2-3 months
Sucking - 4-6 months
Swaddled - 4 months, 1 arm out, if well, both arms, until no bundle
Shhhh sound - 1 year just start to reduce

Daytime Feedings

Wake babies during day, maybe not at night, for feedings

hold-baby.html.title: Hold the Baby
hold-baby.html.body:
Hold the baby
Before holding

Clean hands
Relax, relax shoulders and body
Secure hold, especially the head

Holds

Cradle hold, head on crook of elbow, hand under bottom
Football hold, head on bicep,
Reverse football hold, hand supports neck and head, and feet near elbow
Belly hold, similar to football, but baby is on the stomach
Reverse belly hold, head in hand, baby on stomach
Shoulder hold - have a bib on your shoulder

marriage.html.title: Marriage
marriage.html.body:
Marriage
General tips

Listen to her instead of trying to solve her problems
Don't complain
Offer help unsolicited
Plan time away from the child
Give her compliments
If something is bothering you, see how you can approach it differently
Reduce or eliminate expectations
Say I love you more

What not to say to a new mom

What did you do all day?
That's a mom's job
Are we eating this for dinner, again?
Stop worrying
Why is this house so messy?
Can't you stop the baby from crying? - Baby usually hungry/tired/uncomfortable
Must be nice hanging out with the baby all day
You look tired
Your taking another nap
Are you going to take a shower?
You are not doing that right
When are you going to lose that baby weight?

newborn-care.html.title: Newborn Care
newborn-care.html.body:
Newborn Care
kpdoc.org/newborn
Early behaviors

baby will be very noise making grunts, squeaks, sighs, sneezes and hiccups
baby will recognize familiar voice and react to sounds
baby can distinguish breast milk from any other liquid
make take several weeks for baby's body to unfold from fetal position
vision is best within 8 to 12 inches, so they can see your face, father away, eyes may wander making them look cross-eyed, up to 4 months
baby will be constantly exposed to new sensations, touch is one of the most important
fingernails grow very quickly, trim nails using file, or express breast milk on tip of fingernails



Communication - cues

engagement - focus on your eyes and stare at your face, make sucking motion with lips, smack lips, follow your face and your voice. Trying to tell you something
disengagement - look away from you, or back away from you. Yawn, or cry

Bonding
Important for baby's health

hold your baby often
talk, sing, and read to your baby
Gently massage your baby
cuddle skin to skin(shirts off)
Respond to your baby's needs
Try to limit visitors and other activities during the first few weeks

How to hold a baby
When you want to hold a baby, try to put one hand at bottom of baby, and support neck with other hand. Keep baby close to you.
Feeding your baby
Feed your baby on demand. Early on, baby will feed quite often. In first 24 hours, baby might constantly want to feed.

kp.org/mydoctor/breastfeeding

Burping the baby
Takes 5 to 10 minutes after feeding to burp a baby. Should do it after they breastfeed, but
Tummy time
Babies should have tummy time every day

keep a watchful eye on your baby
Prop up and support your baby with a small rolled up towel or nursing pillow under the chest
Place a mirror on the floor in front of your baby
Get down on the floor, face to face with your baby, and talk or sing. This encourages babies to lift their head and look up
1 to 10 minutes, if baby doesn't fuss, at least 10 minutes
never leave a baby unattended during tummy time

Tips for soothing a baby

Side holding
Swinging
Shushing
Sucking - Wait until crying stops before breastfeeding, try skin to skin after other methods, before starting the feeding
Swaddling

Keeping baby warm or cool - protect from the sun

Babies under 6 months of age should be kept out of direct sunlight
keep your baby in shade and cover their arms, legs, and neck with lightweight clothes
Put baby in one extra layer than what you're wearing yourself - have a blanket just in case

Vaccines

Do them
Make sure visitors are up to date as well

Danger signs - first few weeks to one month

Temperature of 100.4 or higher
Temperature below 97.5
Breaths very fast or hast to work to breath
Vomits frequently
Yellow skin or eyes
Redness and swelling, warm tender skin, pus, or a foul smell coming from umbilical cord
Refuses 2 or more feedings
Is difficult to wake up, not just sleepy
Has problems with circumcision
Has blood in stool

Adventures in sleep
Babies can sleep up to 18 hours a day

0 to 4 months - 18 hours, 3-4 hours at a time
4 to 12 months - 12 hours to 16 hours
1 to 2 years - 11 hours to 14 hours
3 to 5 years - 10 hours to 13 hours

Crib
ABC - Alone Back Crib

sleeb baby alone
sleep baby on their back
sleep baby in crib always
put nothing in baby's sleep area
do not overdress baby
do not smoke around baby

Sleep when baby sleeps

If you ever feel sleepy while holding baby, move baby to bassinet for safety
Getting enough sleep is difficult for all new parents
Line up support for unexpected necessary naps

Umbilical cord
Takes 2 to 4 weeks for stump to heal. SHould fall of on it's own
First baths

Clean eyes outward
Prep bath area before you start
Don't immerse in water before the cord falls off

Is baby eating enough
Number of diapers per days old

1
2
3
4
5 to 6
6 to 8

Tips for Changing baby diapers
For a boy, have washcloths or extra diaper, because when air hits them, they want to pee
For girls, clean from inside out.
Breastfeeding questions

Exclusive for 6 months
mix in solid food afterwards, might be good to introduce peanuts to avoid the allergy

You time

Be patient and compassionate with yourself
Give your body time to heal
Know how to recognize baby blue
More than 2 weeks, call
Don't have unrealistic expectations

sleep-training.html.title: Sleep Training
sleep-training.html.body:
Sleep Training
Pureboost
Tips

wait 3 to 4 months to start training
Stick to a schedule - put baby down to sleep same time
Put them to sleep earlier - try 6 to 6:30 pm
Establish a bedtime routine - bath time, pajamas, read a book, feeding, bed
Remove distractions - get any distractions out of the crib
Put them to sleep before they fall asleep, if they're drowsy, put them in bed first
Feed right before bed
Most learn by 6 to 9 months, longer than that, get help

Methods

Ferber method - allow cry for gradually increasing intervals
Cry it out
No Cry Method - no tears method - pick up baby as soon as it cries, and put it down
